<DOC><DOCNO> AP890518-0289 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 2134EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Macy-Investment     05-18 0258</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Macy-Investment,0270</SECOND><HEAD>Macy Chairman Denies Plans to Divest Divisions</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of R.H. Macy andamp; Co. Thursday saidthe retailer feels its financial footing is secure since it wentprivate in 1986 and it doesn't intend to divest any departmentstore divisions.   Edward S. Finkelstein said there have been persistent rumorsthat Macy's might be planning to sell off some assets.   Some of the speculation in publications and circulating in theretail industry suggests Macy's may be contemplating divestituresdue to concerns about servicing the heavy debt load it took on inits leveraged buyout.   ``We have no intention of selling off any divisions and when wehave been approached we have immediately indicated that ourdivisions are not for sale,'' Finkelstein stated in a letter toinvestors involved in Macy's LBO.   He also stated that Macy's has received inquiries from``interested parties about making an investment in our company.''   ``We listen to and consider all serious ideas,'' he said. ``Thusfar, none have been appropriate for our investors.''   The letter did not identify who has approached Macy's. The WallStreet Journal reported Thursday that specialty apparel retailerLimited Inc. has expressed interest and had preliminary talks withMacy's about making an investment in the New York-based company.   Finkelstein also said Macy's debt structure is sound.   ``The company is well financed and has sufficient liquidity tofund its on-going business as well as capital expenditures for newstores and renovations,'' he said.   Macy's debts are said to total more than $5.2 billion currently.</TEXT></DOC>